Looking at this PR, I'll scan the diff for security, correctness, and logic issues.

## Analysis

**Step 1: Context** — This hook should fetch a user by ID, manage loading/error state, and re-fetch when userId changes.

**Step 2: Full scan** — New file, ~36 lines. Custom hook with async fetch, state management, and a useEffect.

**Step 3: Inspection** — I found several issues:

---

```
[SEVERITY: HIGH] Line 32 — Missing userId dependency in useEffect
Category: logic
Detail: The dependency array is empty [], so the effect runs only once on mount.
The PR description says "re-fetches whenever userId changes", but the hook will
never re-fetch if userId is updated. Fix: change [] to [userId].

[SEVERITY: HIGH] Lines 23–28 — isLoading never set to false
Category: logic
Detail: After setLoading(true), neither the success nor error path calls setLoading(false).
The isLoading state will remain true indefinitely after the first fetch completes,
leaving the UI stuck in a loading state. Add setLoading(false) in a finally block.

[SEVERITY: HIGH] Lines 25–27 — Memory leak on component unmount
Category: memory_leak
Detail: If the component unmounts while the fetch is in flight, setUser() and setError()
will be called on an unmounted component. React will warn "Can't perform a React state
update on an unmounted component". Use a cleanup function with AbortController to cancel
the fetch on unmount, or track whether the component is mounted with a useRef.

[SEVERITY: MEDIUM] Lines 21–29 — Race condition with rapid userId changes
Category: correctness
Detail: If userId changes rapidly while a previous fetch is still in flight, requests
can complete out-of-order and stale data overwrites recent data. Use AbortController
to cancel previous requests before starting a new one.
```

---

**Recommended fix sketch:**
```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  if (!userId) return; // guard against falsy userId
  const controller = new AbortController();

  const load = async () => {
    setLoading(true);
    setError(null); // clear old errors
    try {
      const data = await fetchUser(userId);
      if (!controller.signal.aborted) setUser(data); // only update if not aborted
    } catch (err) {
      if (!controller.signal.aborted) {
        setError(err instanceof Error ? err : new Error('Fetch failed'));
      }
    } finally {
      if (!controller.signal.aborted) setLoading(false); // always clear loading
    }
  };

  load();
  return () => controller.abort(); // cleanup on unmount or userId change
}, [userId]); // re-run when userId changes
```
